It looks like Fires are correlated with Traffic, HGV and Length. Length and HGV are correlated too so we should take this is account when we will try to fit the model.

## Econometric approach We try to look at the effect of HGV in our model. First we regress HGV on Length, the residuals will then capture the pure effect of HGV (because the effect of Length on HGV is already expressed in the betaOLS). So then, I regress Fires on the residuals. The result is that HGV is not that significant.

Reg6 <- lm(HGV ~ Length, data = Fires)
summary(Reg6)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = HGV ~ Length, data = Fires)
## 
## Residuals:
##       Min        1Q    Median        3Q       Max 
## -0.127068 -0.042239 -0.005679  0.030180  0.274060 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 6.771e-02  6.711e-03  10.089  < 2e-16 ***
## Length      1.945e-05  2.508e-06   7.755 8.12e-13 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.07072 on 168 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2636, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2592 
## F-statistic: 60.13 on 1 and 168 DF,  p-value: 8.119e-13
r <- residuals(Reg6)
plot(r)

#by regressing on the residual, we can eliminate the effect of HGV on Length and keep only the effect of Length
Reg7 <- lm(Fires ~r, data=Fires)
summary(Reg7)

By doing it the other way around, we can capture the effect of Length on Fires. It appears to have a greater effect than HGV. However, it is still limited. The thing that appears clearly is the fact that HGV and Length have a strong correlation.

Poisson model

First, I look at the mean to find the parameter.

## [1] 0.8176471

Then I plot the distribution and look at how it looks.

p<-data.frame(rpois(10000,mean(Fires$Fires)))
ggplot(p,aes(x=p[,1]))+
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), alpha=0.4, position="identity", lwd=0.1)+
  geom_density(alpha=0.3, lwd=1, bw=0.2)+
  ggtitle("Poisson model")
